---
layout: base.njk
title: "Family Meal Planner App"
description: "PlateSync builds weekly meal plans with per-person portions based on each family member's health profile. Smart shopping lists, allergy detection, and a mobile cooking guide."
---
{% block head %}
<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "@id": "{{ site.url }}/#faq",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does PlateSync calculate portions?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "It uses the Mifflin-St Jeor equation to calculate daily calorie needs from age, weight, height, sex, and activity level. Protein targets use science-backed ranges (0.9–2.2 g/kg depending on goals). Portions are capped so the total never exceeds the recipe's serving count — you always cook the full batch."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does PlateSync work for kids?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Child profiles support age-appropriate goals, fussy eater notes, texture aversions, preferred foods, and disliked foods. Kids get appropriately smaller portions based on their actual needs."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What happens to leftovers in PlateSync?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "After cooking, you choose what to do with surplus servings: keep in the fridge (4-day expiry), freeze (no expiry), or discard. Leftovers appear as an option when planning future meals — no extra shopping needed."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do nutrition targets change on training days?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. If a family member has a weekly training schedule set up, their calorie and protein targets adjust per day — higher on training days, lower on rest days. Portion tendency also factors in."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I undo a meal if I didn't cook it?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Cooking mode has a Didn't Cook button that returns all ingredients to your pantry — reversing the deduction from when the plan was confirmed."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What cuisines and diets does PlateSync support?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Cuisines include Mediterranean, Asian, Indian, Mexican, Japanese, Korean, Thai, Middle Eastern, American, and African. Diets include balanced, high protein, Mediterranean, keto, paleo, Whole30, vegetarian, and vegan. Each family member can have their own diet preference."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is my data private in PlateSync?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. All household data is secured with row-level security — only members of your household can access your recipes, pantry, and meal plans. No personal health data is ever sent to AI providers."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can multiple people use PlateSync?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. The household owner invites members by email. Everyone shares recipes, pantry, meal plans, and family profiles from their own login."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much does PlateSync cost?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "PlateSync is currently free during early access. Pricing will be announced soon."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "@type": "HowTo",
      "@id": "{{ site.url }}/#how-it-works",
      "name": "How to plan family meals with PlateSync",
      "description": "From family setup to shopping list in minutes — PlateSync handles per-person portions, allergy detection, and leftover tracking.",
      "step": [
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 1,
          "name": "Set up your family",
          "text": "Add each family member with their age, weight, goals, activity level, allergies, and food preferences. PlateSync calculates personalised daily targets for everyone."
        },
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 2,
          "name": "Build your recipe collection",
          "text": "Search the web for recipes using AI, or add your own. PlateSync catalogues each recipe with full ingredients, instructions, and per-serving nutrition."
        },
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 3,
          "name": "Stock your pantry",
          "text": "Log what's already in your fridge, pantry, and freezer. Type or dictate a list and AI sorts it for you. PlateSync uses this to rank recipes and subtract ingredients from your shopping list."
        },
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 4,
          "name": "Plan your week",
          "text": "Assign recipes to each day. The app ranks recipes by what you already have on hand and flags any allergy conflicts. Portions are calculated per person, capped to the recipe's actual serving count."
        },
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 5,
          "name": "Shop smart",
          "text": "Confirm your plan and get a shopping list with full-batch ingredient amounts — what you actually buy and cook. Pantry items are subtracted so you only buy what you need."
        },
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 6,
          "name": "Cook with a guide",
          "text": "Tap any meal on your phone to open cooking mode: checkable ingredients, step-by-step instructions, and a clear breakdown of how much to plate for each person. No ads, no life story — just the recipe."
        },
        {
          "@type": "HowToStep",
          "position": 7,
          "name": "Handle leftovers",
          "text": "After cooking, mark the meal as done. Surplus servings can be kept in the fridge, frozen, or discarded. Leftovers show up as an option for future meals — no extra shopping."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
</script>
{% endblock %}

